>>45993447
Do not quit
First, it does come across. It comes across a lot; that's kind of what's so frustrating. The story totally seems like it's going somewhere; it's chock-full of intrigue, some of which I found really fascinating. But some of those questions you can't bait long, not with the tone you're keeping. The big, immediate ones all have to do with why Leo, who was convinced Missie didn't and couldn't exist, is so comfortable with her as to be annoyed by her from the get -go, as opposed to awe-stricken, terrified, or perhaps overjoyed. It's a really cool twist, actually. What's more: it's a frightening twist. The fact that Leo isn't worried raises massive questions about him and the world he lives in, and they're not casual questions. It's psychological horror. The story really implies that that question is going to be the crux of the plot, but it started to lose me after I got four or five chapters in without much apparent hope of headway on that front. I'm not suggesting you need to answer it right away; quite the opposite. But you do need to give us a peek behind the curtain right away. You have to confirm our fears a little bit and satiate parts of our curiosity. We have to know for sure that there's something to find, and we have to spend real, active time looking for that thing. Love it or hate it, Wandavision is a pretty good example of this kind of thing. Twin Peaks, too. You've put yourself in a bit of an unreliable narrator corner, but you can't pull a Fight Club with Missy and Leo. That relationship appeared normal at first. This one appears exotic from the start.

Don't make the mistake I did. Don't be afraid to go back and revise large sections of the story you've already posted.
